description:
Create src/routes/run.rs with the streaming path (Accept: text/event-stream): (1) Parse optional JSON body for overrides. (2) Check sequential enforcement. (3) Check round status state machine. (4) Acquire lock. (5) Write round record with status=running. (6) Read workflow config, resolve provider/model/system_prompt with overrides. (7) Select template, bundle documents, detect warnings. (8) Open LLM stream via provider adapter. (9) Create a TransformStream: for each StreamChunk::Text, append to buffer AND write 'event: token
data: {text}

' to the client stream. On StreamChunk::Usage, store. On StreamChunk::Done, run on-complete hook (T9_5), then write 'event: done
data: {summary}

'. On error, write 'event: error
data: {details}

', save failed round. (10) Return Response with Content-Type: text/event-stream and the transform stream body. This is the most complex handler. See PRD sections 5.5 (POST /run), 7.4.

Create src/routes/run.rs — the main round execution handler. Both streaming and non-streaming paths in one function: (1) Parse optional JSON body for overrides (include_impl, skip_sequence_check, provider, model, system_prompt, provider_params). Missing body or {} = use workflow defaults. (2) Run pre-run validation (sequence check + status machine). (3) Acquire lock, write round record status=running. (4) Read workflow config, resolve provider/model/system_prompt with per-run overrides. (5) Select template (impl_every_n logic), bundle documents from KV, detect warnings. (6) Open LLM stream via provider adapter. STREAMING PATH (Accept: text/event-stream): Create TransformStream — for each Text chunk, append to buffer + write 'event:token
data:{text}

'. On Usage, store. On Done, run on-complete hook then write 'event:done
data:{summary}

'. On error, write 'event:error', save failed round. Return Response with text/event-stream. NON-STREAMING PATH (default/Accept:application/json): Consume provider stream to completion, buffer all text. Run on-complete hook. Return full round record in standard JSON envelope. This is the most complex handler — see PRD sections 5.5, 7.4, 7.5.
